\begin_layout Subsection
Uncertainty with perfect agency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In reality however, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is never observed.
 The level of severity for the patients is a random variable represented
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, characterized by a subjective cdf.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F(s),$
\end_inset

with density 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a realization of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value of choosing an admissible treatment intensity
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(t,S)=E[u(t,s)]=\max_{t}\int_{S}u(t,s)dF(s)\label{eq:expected-utility-prior}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is however possible to acquire costly information about 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 through medical diagnostics and physician effort.
 However, for two experiment 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, it is not a priori certain that one experiment 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is necessary more 
\emph on
informative
\emph default
 about 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 than the experiment 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, where 
\emph on
informative
\emph default
 is to be understood in the way the posterior decision induced by the experiment
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 insures greater expected utility than the decision induced by the experiment
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we must introduce an order of information.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:afflilation"

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Milgrom1982"

\end_inset

) For a family of density functions, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\lor s$
\end_inset

 denote the component wise maximum and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\land s$
\end_inset

 the component wise minimum.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are affiliated if, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(s\lor x)f(s\land x)\ge f(s)f(x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Affiliation of two random variables are equivalent to the monotone likelihood
 ration property, and the intuition behind definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:afflilation"

\end_inset

 is that higher signal realization of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 makes the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is large, higher.
 Similarly small signal realization of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 makes the probability of a small 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 more likely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:accuracy"

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Acquisition2000"

\end_inset

) Given two signals (experiments) 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta'}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta'}$
\end_inset

 is more accurate than 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T(x)=F^{\eta'^{-1}}(F^{\eta}(x\mid s)\mid s)\label{eq:acuracy tranformation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 is non decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A family of signals 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X^{\eta}\right\} _{\eta\in E}$
\end_inset

 is accuracy ordered (A-ordered) if a signal with higher index is more accurate
 than a signal with lower index.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the concept of accuracy, it can be noted that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(X^{\eta}\mid s)\sim X^{\eta'}\mid s
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus a more accurate signal can be obtained from a less accurate signal,
 by the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T(X)$
\end_inset

.
 An illustrative example can also be given by applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\eqref{eq:acuracy tranformation}$
\end_inset

 to hypothesis testing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 can take two values 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}<s_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

 be a information structure affiliated with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The optimal test based on 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is given by the rejection region 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}>x^{*}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

 is rejected in favor of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}>x^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of a type I error is then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}(X^{\eta}\le x^{*})=F(x^{*}\mid s_{2})$
\end_inset

 and the probability of a type II error is 
\begin_inset Formula $1-F(x^{*}\mid s_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Now given that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta'}$
\end_inset

 is more accurate than 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is is possible to design a test with the same probability of type I error,
 by choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{**}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x^{**}\mid s_{2})=F(x^{*}\mid s_{2})$
\end_inset

 (e.i.
 accept 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}\ge x^{**}$
\end_inset

).
 However, since 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta'}$
\end_inset

 is more accurate than 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{**}\ge F^{\eta'^{-1}}(F^{\eta}(x\mid s_{1})\mid s_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{**}$
\end_inset

 lies on or, to the right of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 then the test based on 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta'}$
\end_inset

 is a least as powerful as the test based on 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lehmann1988,Acquisition2000"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be distributed according to any CDF and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\eta}\sim\mathbb{U}(s-1/\eta,s+1/\eta)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta'>\eta$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\eta'}{2}=\frac{\eta}{2}\left(T^{-1}(x)\right)'\Leftrightarrow T(x)=\frac{\eta}{\eta'}(x-s)+s
\]

\end_inset

 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $T(x)$
\end_inset

 transforms 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta'}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Persico1996"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Acquisition2000"

\end_inset

) Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta'}$
\end_inset

 are affiliated with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X^{\eta}\right\} _{\eta\in E}$
\end_inset

 is A-ordered, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta'}$
\end_inset

 is more accurate than 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all utility functions with a single crossing property 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta'}$
\end_inset

 is more informative than 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\eta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

